[Music in background throughout.]
[Bank of America
®
logo shown periodically throughout video.]
On screen copy:
Bank of America's Children's Safety Rules
Hey kids. This video is to help those 12 and younger understand the rules we follow to keep your information safe when using a Bank of America account.
For children 13 or older, your online access may include additional features, so we suggest reading our Children's Privacy Policy on our website with your parent to learn more.
On screen copy:
13 and older
There is a law that helps protect children younger than 13 called the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act.
On screen copy:
Safe
This law lets parents do more with the account such as allowing us to use the information you give us.
To make this easier for you to understand, we're going to break this down into three parts:
1. Who can use the account
2. Information we get from you or your parent
3. What the bank can see when you use the account
On screen copy:
3 parts
1 - 2 - 3
Let's start with #1 — who can use the account.
On screen copy:
#1
You use this account with your parent. We do this because it allows you to learn about spending and saving money - with their help. This means they can see everything you do on the account, including how you spend the money.
On screen copy:
Receipt
Parents can also set up alerts that tell them if you use your card to buy something and control how much money you spend or where you spend it.
On screen copy:
Alerts
Your parent can choose how we talk with you, as well as tell us to remove information about you from our computers.
Let's move onto #2 on our list, information we get from you or your parent.
On screen copy:
#2
It's important to know that when you use the bank account or visit our website, we may ask for some things that are unique to just you, such as your name, birthday and even where you live — the types of things you would never tell a stranger. We need this kind of information about you so you can use the bank account and so we can talk with you or your parent about the account.
We'll only ask you for it if we need it, and we won't share it unless we have to. Your parent may have already given us some of this information so don't worry if you don't know all of the answers.
On screen copy:
Won't share
If your parent lets you use our mobile app or go online to use your account, you may see things that make our app easier to use. Because these things have extra rules you must follow before you can use them, please have your parent help you set up your account.
On screen copy:
Extra rules
Things that help tell us who you are, like when you use your face or thumbprint to log into your account, are part of the device you are using; we can't see that kind of stuff.
This brings us to #3, what the bank can see when you use the account.
On screen copy:
#3
Our computers gather information about how you use the account such as the things you buy or where you bought something. They can also see things like your phone number or the number on your card.
When you visit our website, our computers collect things called cookies. These are different than the kind of cookies you eat. Cookies are tiny pieces of information that only our computers can see. Cookies help us remember things about you like your name or the places you like to spend your money.
On screen copy:
Cookies
There are different types of cookies, some we keep for just a short time and some we keep for a bit longer. We have a whole section about cookies on our website if you or your parent wants to learn more.
On screen copy:
Learn more
For now, it's important for you to understand that the information we get from you, and what our computers can see, helps us make things better for you when using the account. It can also help us tell if someone uses the account without your permission since only you and your parent are allowed to use the account.
Bank of America must follow rules just like you. Sometimes the rules change, and if they do, we'll be sure to let you know on our privacy page.
On screen copy:
Privacy Page
If there is anything that you didn't understand in this video, please talk with your parent. They can read the Privacy Rights section on this webpage for more information. Thank you for watching!
